2. What is the “Rule of Thirds” in layout design?
The Rule of Thirds is a visual design principle that divides a layout into 3 equal horizontal and 3 equal vertical sections (like a tic-tac-toe grid).
Important elements (text, images, buttons) are placed along the lines or at intersections.
Purpose: Makes the design more balanced, visually appealing, and easier for users to focus on key content.

3. Why should you limit the number of font families used on a website?
Using too many fonts creates visual clutter and looks unprofessional.
Consistency: Fewer fonts improve user experience and help brand recognition.
Performance: Loading multiple fonts can slow down page loading speed.
Rule of Thumb: Usually 1–2 font families are enough (one for headings, one for body text).

4. Define “Responsive Web Design”
Responsive Web Design (RWD) is an approach to designing websites so that they automatically adjust and look good on all devices (desktops, tablets, mobiles).
Techniques used: Flexible grids, flexible images, media queries (CSS).
Purpose: Enhances usability, accessibility, and SEO.

