5.Explain the ”F-Pattern” of scanning and how it influences the placement of content on a web page.
The F-Pattern describes how users typically read or scan web pages, especially pages with lots of 
text, such as articles or search results. Eye-tracking studies show that users’ eyes move in a 
pattern resembling the letter “F”:
Top Horizontal Movement:
Users first scan across the top of the page (the first horizontal line), reading headings or the 
first few words.
This is the most attention-grabbing area.

Second Horizontal Movement:
Users then scan a shorter horizontal line below the first, usually across subheadings or important phrases.

Vertical Scan:
Finally, users scan the left side vertically, quickly glancing down the page.
They focus on the beginning of each line, ignoring much of the content on the right.
Influence on Content Placement

Place important content on the top-left:
Headlines, key messages, and call-to-actions (CTAs) should be near the top or left side of the page.

Use headings, bullet points, and short paragraphs:
Helps users quickly find what they are looking for as they scan vertically.

Highlight important keywords on the first few words of lines:
Ensures critical information is seen even if the user only glances at the left side.

Images and buttons:
Should align with the natural scanning pattern, e.g., top or along the F’s horizontal bars.

