8. A website loads very slowly, causing users to abandon it. Upon inspection, you find the
developer used high-resolution raw images directly from a camera. Explain the importance
of Image Optimization and file formats (JPEG vs PNG) to solve this
A website is slow because high-resolution raw images were used directly from a camera. Users leave before the page loads.

Importance of Image Optimization
Image optimization means reducing file size without compromising visual quality to improve:

Website Speed:
Smaller images load faster, reducing page load time.
Faster pages increase user engagement and reduce bounce rates.

SEO Benefits:
Search engines like Google prioritize fast-loading websites.
Optimized images improve overall page ranking.

Better User Experience:
Quick-loading pages retain users and improve satisfaction.
Mobile users benefit especially due to limited bandwidth.

Reduced Bandwidth and Storage:
Smaller images consume less server space and data.

Choosing File Formats: JPEG vs PNG
File Format	Best For	Pros	Cons
JPEG	Photographs, realistic images	High compression, small file size	Loses some quality (lossy), 
not ideal for transparency PNG	Logos, icons, images with transparency	Lossless, supports transparency	
Larger file size compared to JPEG, not ideal for photos

Rule of Thumb:
Use JPEG for photos or complex images where file size matters.
Use PNG for graphics, logos, or images that require transparency.
How to Solve the Problem
Resize Images:
Reduce image dimensions to what’s actually needed on the web.
Compress Images:
Use tools like TinyPNG, ImageOptim, or Photoshop “Save for Web.”
Choose Appropriate Format:
JPEG for photos, PNG for graphics/logos.

Lazy Loading (Optional):
Load images only when users scroll to them to save initial page load time.

Summary:
Optimized images with the correct file format make websites faster, user-friendly, and SEO-friendly,
preventing users from abandoning the site.

