10.A website looks great on a laptop but is unreadable on a mobile phone because the user has to zoom in and scroll horizontally. Identify the design principle missing here and explain how Media Queries/Fluid Grids could fix it
A website looks fine on a laptop but is unreadable on mobile, requiring zooming and horizontal scrolling.
Missing Design Principle
Responsive Web Design (RWD) is missing.
Principle: A website should adapt its layout, images, and content to different screen sizes and devices.
Without responsiveness:
Users on mobile have poor experience.
Text may be too small.
Horizontal scrolling frustrates users.
How to Fix Using Media Queries and Fluid Grids
1. Media Queries (CSS)
Media queries allow different styles for different screen sizes.

Example:

/* For mobile devices (up to 600px width) */
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  body {
    font-size: 16px;       /* Increase readability */
    padding: 10px;         /* Avoid content touching edges */
  }
  nav {
    display: block;        /* Stack menu items vertically */
  }
}

Effect: Layout adjusts automatically for smaller screens.

2. Fluid Grids
Instead of fixed pixel widths, use relative units (%, em, rem) for elements:
Columns, images, and containers scale proportionally.
Example:
container {
  width: 90%;      /* Scales with screen size */
  margin: 0 auto;  /* Center container */
}

Effect: Content fits the screen width without horizontal scrolling.



